issue.title: Migrate to null safety and support Dart 3
issue.body:
Linkcheck needs to migrate to support sound null safety to allow developers with a Dart 3 dev SDK to run it.

This PR also moves away from a from-to-map based solution for passing messages between isolates. It was a bit messy once migrated to null safety, and the objects can be passed directly instead. To maintain the same system where workers stay alive due to their HTTP connections, messages are now specified within a `WorkerTask` with a `WorkerVerb` enum specifying its type. Messages are shared when immutable and automatically copied when not. I didn't run any benchmarks, but I imagine it may result in some speed ups too due to avoiding some unnecessary object constructions as well as simpler comparisons.

\cc @domesticmouse and @khanhnwin As this will be needed for dart-lang/site-www (sooner) and flutter/website (later)

comment.body: Thanks for the review! I hope to test the changes further and likely make some other cleanup changes over the next few days, but it's nice to see the primary migration be complete.

Makes sense, thanks for the context. With the introduction of lightweight isolates(https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/issues/36097), they also expanded and more explicitly outlined what can be sent(https://api.dart.dev/stable/2.18.5/dart-isolate/SendPort/send.html) so I think platform support should be fine now. 

I believe the sent objects are also immediately copied, so I don't think there should be any issues during/after the copy, but I'll be on the look out. There could be further benefits to making more of the messages sent deeply immutable, even if just in terms of following the code and avoiding any of those concerns.

I guess it's likely https://github.com/dart-lang/dartdoc/pull/2600 or related changes which includes annotations as features, which are [rendered](https://github.com/dart-lang/dartdoc/blob/master/lib/templates/html/method.html#L11), but annotations are still [rendered as well](https://github.com/dart-lang/dartdoc/blob/master/lib/templates/html/_callable_multiline.html#L4).

issue.body:
### Page URL

### Page source

https://github.com/dart-lang/site-www/tree/main/src/tools/pub/environment-variables.md

### Describe the problem

Where can we set these environment variables so that they will be **always** available when we run e.g., `flutter pub get`. I'm referring to when someone might miss exporting the env manually; we'll need some pre-build hook that allows us to ship the variable.

### Expected fix

_No response_

### Additional context

_No response_

comment.body:
Thanks for opening an issue! Do you mean how to specify them so they persist across terminal sessions or do you mean share them for everyone running the commands in the project?

For the first case, specifying how to set environment variables is something we've mostly not documented as it is different across operating systems and versions, as well as between different shells occasionally, plus it's not really specific to Dart. Perhaps we could include a page discussing some common methods of doing so and link to it from here as well as any other necessary locations if there's enough of a desire.

As for the second case, pub environment variables are meant to be per user rather than tied to a project as each developer each may want to specify their own cache location or need to use their own mirror depending on their location.

issue.title: Migrate to null safety and support Dart 3
issue.body:
Linkcheck needs to migrate to support sound null safety to allow developers with a Dart 3 dev SDK to run it.

This PR also moves away from a from-to-map based solution for passing messages between isolates. It was a bit messy once migrated to null safety, and the objects can be passed directly instead. To maintain the same system where workers stay alive due to their HTTP connections, messages are now specified within a `WorkerTask` with a `WorkerVerb` enum specifying its type. Messages are shared when immutable and automatically copied when not. I didn't run any benchmarks, but I imagine it may result in some speed ups too due to avoiding some unnecessary object constructions as well as simpler comparisons.

\cc @domesticmouse and @khanhnwin As this will be needed for dart-lang/site-www (sooner) and flutter/website (later)

comment.body: Thanks for the review! I hope to test the changes further and likely make some other cleanup changes over the next few days, but it's nice to see the primary migration be complete.

Makes sense, thanks for the context. With the introduction of lightweight isolates(https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/issues/36097), they also expanded and more explicitly outlined what can be sent(https://api.dart.dev/stable/2.18.5/dart-isolate/SendPort/send.html) so I think platform support should be fine now. 

I believe the sent objects are also immediately copied, so I don't think there should be any issues during/after the copy, but I'll be on the look out. There could be further benefits to making more of the messages sent deeply immutable, even if just in terms of following the code and avoiding any of those concerns.

### Describe the problem

Where can we set these environment variables so that they will be **always** available when we run e.g., `flutter pub get`. I'm referring to when someone might miss exporting the env manually; we'll need some pre-build hook that allows us to ship the variable.

### Expected fix

_No response_

_No response_

comment.body:
Thanks for opening an issue! Do you mean how to specify them so they persist across terminal sessions or do you mean share them for everyone running the commands in the project?

For the first case, specifying how to set environment variables is something we've mostly not documented as it is different across operating systems and versions, as well as between different shells occasionally, plus it's not really specific to Dart. Perhaps we could include a page discussing some common methods of doing so and link to it from here as well as any other necessary locations if there's enough of a desire.

As for the second case, pub environment variables are meant to be per user rather than tied to a project as each developer each may want to specify their own cache location or need to use their own mirror depending on their location.

issue.title: Migrate to null safety and support Dart 3
issue.body:
Linkcheck needs to migrate to support sound null safety to allow developers with a Dart 3 dev SDK to run it.

This PR also moves away from a from-to-map based solution for passing messages between isolates. It was a bit messy once migrated to null safety, and the objects can be passed directly instead. To maintain the same system where workers stay alive due to their HTTP connections, messages are now specified within a `WorkerTask` with a `WorkerVerb` enum specifying its type. Messages are shared when immutable and automatically copied when not. I didn't run any benchmarks, but I imagine it may result in some speed ups too due to avoiding some unnecessary object constructions as well as simpler comparisons.

\cc @domesticmouse and @khanhnwin As this will be needed for dart-lang/site-www (sooner) and flutter/website (later)

comment.body: Thanks for the review! I hope to test the changes further and likely make some other cleanup changes over the next few days, but it's nice to see the primary migration be complete.

Makes sense, thanks for the context. With the introduction of lightweight isolates(https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/issues/36097), they also expanded and more explicitly outlined what can be sent(https://api.dart.dev/stable/2.18.5/dart-isolate/SendPort/send.html) so I think platform support should be fine now. 

I believe the sent objects are also immediately copied, so I don't think there should be any issues during/after the copy, but I'll be on the look out. There could be further benefits to making more of the messages sent deeply immutable, even if just in terms of following the code and avoiding any of those concerns.

issue.title: [PAGE ISSUE]: 'Configuring pub environment variables'
issue.body:
### Page URL

https://dart.dev/tools/pub/environment-variables.html

### Page source

https://github.com/dart-lang/site-www/tree/main/src/tools/pub/environment-variables.md

### Describe the problem

Where can we set these environment variables so that they will be **always** available when we run e.g., `flutter pub get`. I'm referring to when someone might miss exporting the env manually; we'll need some pre-build hook that allows us to ship the variable.

### Expected fix

_No response_

### Additional context

_No response_

comment.body:
Thanks for opening an issue! Do you mean how to specify them so they persist across terminal sessions or do you mean share them for everyone running the commands in the project?

For the first case, specifying how to set environment variables is something we've mostly not documented as it is different across operating systems and versions, as well as between different shells occasionally, plus it's not really specific to Dart. Perhaps we could include a page discussing some common methods of doing so and link to it from here as well as any other necessary locations if there's enough of a desire.

As for the second case, pub environment variables are meant to be per user rather than tied to a project as each developer each may want to specify their own cache location or need to use their own mirror depending on their location.
